=== United States ===
[[Timothy McVeigh]], the main perpetrator of the 1995 [[Oklahoma City bombing]] that killed 168 and injured more than 680, carried pages from ''[[The Turner Diaries]],'' a fictional account of white supremacists who ignite a revolution by blowing up the FBI headquarters with a truck bomb.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,986240-1,00.html |title=Oklahoma City: The Weight of Evidence |last=Collins |first=James |author2=Patrick E. Cole |author3=Elaine Shannon|author-link3=Elaine Shannon |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |pages=1–8 |date=28 April 1997 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211193636/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,986240-1,00.html |archive-date=11 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The book was greatly influential in shaping white nationalism and in the later development of white genocide conspiracy theory.<ref name="RossK" /><ref name="Berger" /> Although the bomber did not attribute his motives to the white nationalist movement, he frequently cited ''The Turner Diaries'' and had been reprimanded in the Army for wearing a "white power" T-shirt purchased at a [[Ku Klux Klan]] rally.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mull |first1=Jeremy |title=Timothy James McVeigh #717 |url=http://www.clarkprosecutor.org/html/death/US/mcveigh717.htm |website=www.clarkprosecutor.org |publisher=Office of the Clark County Prosecuting Attorney |access-date=16 November 2019}}</ref>

[[Richard Baumhammers]], the perpetrator of a 2000 shooting spree in [[Pittsburgh]], Pennsylvania, that killed five people and injured a sixth, complained that European Americans are being outnumbered by minorities and immigrants, calling on a website for "an end to non-white immigration" because "almost all" present day immigration "is non-European."<ref>{{cite news |title=Inspiring Extremist Crimes |url=http://www.adl.org/internet/extremism_rw/inspiring.asp |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925190132/http://www.adl.org/internet/extremism_rw/inspiring.asp |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 September 2012 |access-date=1 September 2019 |work=Anti-Defamation League |date=25 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Randall |first1=Kate |title=Five killed in racist shooting rampage in Pittsburgh – World Socialist Web Site |url=https://www.wsws.org/en/articles/2000/05/pitt-m02.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413025741/https://www.wsws.org/en/articles/2000/05/pitt-m02.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 April 2019 |access-date=1 September 2019 |work=International Committee of the Fourth International |date=2 May 2000}}</ref>

[[Frazier Glenn Miller Jr.]], the perpetrator of [[Overland Park Jewish Community Center shooting|a shooting spree]] that killed three people at a Jewish community center and retirement home in [[Overland Park, Kansas]], had supported the slogan: "Diversity is code for white genocide."<ref>{{cite news|title=Three Kansas men convicted over mass 'slaughter' plot targeting Muslims |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/apr/18/kansas-terror-plot-kill-muslims-conviction |work=[[The Guardian]]|date=18 April 2018}}</ref> He stated that the "systematic genocide of white people by Jews" was his motive,<ref>{{cite news|title=White Supremacist Convicted of Killing 3 at Kansas Jewish Centers |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/01/us/white-supremacist-convicted-of-killing-3-at-kansas-jewish-centers.html |work=[[New York Times]] |date=31 August 2015}}</ref> and that he, "had a patriotic intent to stop genocide against my people".<ref>{{cite news|title=Kansas City JCC shooter claims he was trying 'to stop genocide' |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/kansas-city-jcc-shooter-says-he-was-trying-to-stop-genocide/ |work=[[Times of Israel]] |date=29 August 2015}}</ref> On [[Easter Sunday]], the day after the shooting, white supremacists delivered "white genocide" themed [[Easter eggs]] to several houses in [[Henrico County, Virginia]], repeating the "Diversity = white genocide" mantra.<ref>{{cite news|title=White Supremacists Plant Racist Easter Eggs |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/cheats/2014/04/22/white-supremacists-plant-racist-easter-eggs |work=[[Daily Beast]] |date=17 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Racist Easter Eggs Left On Lawn Outrage Parents |url= https://www.huffpost.com/entry/racist-easter-eggs_n_5186893 |work=[[HuffPost]] |date=21 April 2014}}</ref>

[[Dylann Roof]], the perpetrator of the [[Charleston church shooting]] that killed nine people and injured a tenth, included a photo on his [[Facebook]] page of him wearing a jacket decorated with two [[emblem]]s that are popular among American [[white supremacist]]s: the [[Flag of Rhodesia|flag of the former Rhodesia]] (now known as Zimbabwe) and [[Flag of South Africa (1928–1994)|the flag of]] [[South Africa under apartheid|apartheid-era South Africa]].<ref name="nyt-ccs">{{cite web|title=Charleston Church Shooting Suspect, Dylann Storm Roof, Is Captured|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/19/us/charleston-church-shooting.html|work=The New York Times|date=18 June 2015|access-date=18 June 2015}}</ref><ref name="nyt-facebook">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/19/us/on-facebook-dylann-roof-charleston-suspect-wears-symbols-of-white-supremacy.html|title=On Facebook, Dylann Roof, Charleston Suspect, Wears Symbols of White Supremacy|work=The New York Times|date=18 June 2015|access-date=18 June 2015}}</ref><ref name="dailybeast">{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/cheats/2015/06/18/charleston-suspect-is-dylann-roof.html|title=Everything Known About Charleston Church Shooting Suspect Dylann Roof|work=The Daily Beast|date=18 June 2015|access-date=18 June 2015}}</ref> He had been blogging on a website called "The Last Rhodesian" (www.lastrhodesian.com) registered on 9 February 2015,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Home — My website |url=http://lastrhodesian.com/ |date=20 June 2015 |access-date=20 June 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620134455/http://lastrhodesian.com/ |archive-date=20 June 2015 }}</ref><ref name=Robles20June>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/21/us/dylann-storm-roof-photos-website-charleston-church-shooting.html|title=Dylann Storm Roof Photos Found on Website|last=Robles|first=Francis|newspaper=The New York Times|date=20 June 2015|access-date=20 June 2015}}</ref><ref name="Gawker">{{Cite web|title=Here Is What Appears to Be Dylann Roof's Racist Manifesto |url=http://gawker.com/here-is-what-appears-to-be-dylann-roofs-racist-manifest-1712767241 |work=Gawker |date=20 June 2015 |access-date=20 June 2015 |first=Brendan |last=O'Connor |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620195150/http://gawker.com/here-is-what-appears-to-be-dylann-roofs-racist-manifest-1712767241 |archive-date=20 June 2015 }}</ref> which included an unsigned manifesto containing his opinions of "Blacks", "Jews", "Hispanics" and "East Asians".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.thenation.com/blog/210537/two-degrees-separation-between-dylann-roof-and-republican-party|title=The 2 Degrees of Separation Between Dylann Roof and the Republican Party|magazine=The Nation|date=22 June 2015|access-date=23 June 2015|first=Michelle|last=Goldberg}}</ref><ref name=Lewis21June>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/jun/20/dylann-roof-fbi-website-manifesto-charleston-shooting|title=Dylann Roof: FBI probes manifesto and website linked to Charleston suspect|work=The Guardian|date=21 June 2015|access-date=21 June 2015|first1=Paul|last1=Lewis|first2=Amanda|last2=Holpuch|first3=Jessica|last3=Glenza}}</ref> Saying he became "racially aware" as a result of the 2012 [[killing of Trayvon Martin]], he wrote that because he kept hearing people talk about the incident, he "decided to look him up" and read the [[Wikipedia]] article about it. He concluded that [[George Zimmerman]] had been in the right, and was unable to comprehend why the case had gained national attention. He said he then searched for black on white crime on [[Google]] and found the website of the [[Council of Conservative Citizens]], where he read "pages upon pages" of cases involving black people murdering white people, stating that he had "never been the same since that day."<ref name = "Gawker"/> For these reasons, Federal prosecutors said he was "self-radicalized" online, instead of adopting his white supremacist ideology through personal associations or experiences with white supremacists.<ref name="WashPost.Self">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2016/08/22/prosecutors-say-accused-charleston-church-gunman-self-radicalized-online/|title=Prosecutors say Dylann Roof 'self-radicalized' online, wrote another manifesto in jail|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=23 August 2016|access-date=23 August 2016|first=Mark|last=Berman}}</ref>

The driver responsible for the [[Charlottesville car attack]] against protesters at the [[Unite the Right rally]] had previously espoused [[neo-Nazi]] and white supremacist beliefs.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pilcher|first1=James|title=Charlottesville suspect's beliefs were 'along the party lines of the neo-Nazi movement,' ex-teacher says|url=https://eu.cincinnati.com/story/news/local/northern-ky/2017/08/13/charlottesville-suspects-beliefs-were-along-party-lines-neo-nazi-movement-ex-teacher-says/563139001/|website=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]|access-date=26 May 2018|language=en|date=14 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Pilcher|first1=James|title=Charlottesville suspect's beliefs were 'along the party lines of the neo-Nazi movement,' ex-teacher says|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2017/08/13/charlottesville-suspects-views-neo-nazi-ex-teacher/563199001/|website=[[USA Today]]|access-date=26 May 2018|language=en|date=14 August 2017}}</ref> He had driven from Ohio to join the rally in which participants chanted, "Jews will not replace us."<ref name="Pearce">{{cite news |first=Matt |last=Pearce |date=11 August 2017 |url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-white-virginia-rally-20170811-story.html |url-status=live|access-date=30 September 2021 |title=Chanting 'blood and soil!' white nationalists with torches march on University of Virginia |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170812100509/http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-white-virginia-rally-20170811-story.html|archive-date=12 August 2017 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times }}</ref> He killed one person and injured 28.

[[File:Tree of Life – Or L'Simcha synagogue facade.jpg|thumb|right|Memorials to victims of the mass shooting outside the [[Tree of Life – Or L'Simcha Congregation|Tree of Life synagogue]] in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, on 4 November 2018]]

The perpetrator of the [[Pittsburgh synagogue shooting]] that killed eleven and injured another seven wrote "Jews are the children of Satan" in his social media profile, using neo-Nazi and white supremacist symbolism associated with David Lane, along with the Nazi slogan, "''Heil Hitler.''"<ref>{{cite news |last=Beckett |first=Lois |date=27 October 2018 |title=Pittsburgh shooting: suspect railed against Jews and Muslims on site used by 'alt-right' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/oct/27/pittsburgh-shooting-suspect-antisemitism |work=The Guardian |access-date=27 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181028000919/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/oct/27/pittsburgh-shooting-suspect-antisemitism |archive-date=28 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> He supported white genocide conspiracy theories, writing in one instance, "Daily Reminder: Diversity means chasing down the last white person."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pennsylvania-shooting-suspect/who-is-robert-bowers-the-pittsburgh-synagogue-shooting-suspect-idUSKCN1N10S6|title=Who is Robert Bowers, the Pittsburgh synagogue shooting suspect?|last=Renshaw|first=Jarriett|date=27 October 2018|work=Reuters|access-date=21 January 2018}}</ref> He also wrote diatribes against white women who have relationships with black men.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2018/10/what-we-know-about-robert-bowers-alleged-synagogue-shooter.html|title=What We Know About Robert Bowers, Alleged Pittsburgh Synagogue Shooter|last=Raymond|first=Adam K.|work=Intelligencer|access-date=29 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029101418/http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2018/10/what-we-know-about-robert-bowers-alleged-synagogue-shooter.html|archive-date=29 October 2018|url-status=live }}</ref> In the weeks before the shooting, Bowers made anti-Semitic posts directed at the [[HIAS|Hebrew Immigrant Aid Society]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/10/27/661409410/whats-known-about-robert-bowers-the-suspect-in-the-pittsburgh-synagogue-shooting|title=What's Known About Robert Bowers, The Suspect In The Pittsburgh Synagogue Shooting|last=Shannon|first=Sant|date=27 October 2018|publisher=[[NPR]]|access-date=27 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181027233340/https://www.npr.org/2018/10/27/661409410/whats-known-about-robert-bowers-the-suspect-in-the-pittsburgh-synagogue-shooting|archive-date=27 October 2018|url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/5437006/gab-social-media-robert-bowers/|title=How Gab Became the Social Media Site Where the Pittsburgh Suspect's Anti-Semitism Thrived|trans-title=Why Gab Allowed Pittsburgh Suspect's Anti-Semitism to Thrive|last=Vesoulis|first=Abby|date=27 October 2018|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=27 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181028140228/http://time.com/5437006/gab-social-media-robert-bowers/|archive-date=28 October 2018|url-status=live }}</ref> who sponsor the National Refugee Shabbat.<ref name="National Refugee Shabbat">{{cite web |url=https://www.hias.org/national-refugee-shabbat |title=National Refugee Shabbat |publisher=Hebrew Immigrant Aid Society |access-date=28 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181028195816/https://www.hias.org/national-refugee-shabbat |archive-date=28 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Shortly before the attack, in an apparent reference to [[immigrants to the United States]], he posted on [[Gab (social network)|Gab]] that "HIAS likes to bring invaders in that kill our people. I can't sit by and watch my people get slaughtered. Screw your optics, I'm going in."<ref>{{cite news |first1=Eric |last1=Levenson |first2=Ray |last2=Sanchez |title=Mass shooting at Pittsburgh synagogue |url=https://www.cnn.com/us/live-news/pittsburgh-synagogue-shooting/index.html |publisher=CNN |date=27 October 2018 |access-date=27 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181027170709/https://www.cnn.com/us/live-news/pittsburgh-synagogue-shooting/index.html |archive-date=27 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Kragie 2018">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/10/pittsburgh-synagogue-comes-amid-surge-anti-semiticism/574180/|title=The Synagogue Killings Mark a Surge of Anti-Semitism|last=Kragie|first=Andrew|date=27 October 2018|work=[[The Atlantic]]|access-date=27 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181027214512/https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/10/pittsburgh-synagogue-comes-amid-surge-anti-semiticism/574180/|archive-date=27 October 2018|url-status=live }}</ref>

The perpetrator of the [[Poway synagogue shooting]] that killed one and injured three others blamed Jews for white genocide, which he described as the "meticulously planned genocide of the European race" in his manifesto.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2019/04/28/shooting-poway-synagogue-underscores-link-between-internet-radicalization-and-violence |title=Shooting at Poway Synagogue Underscores Link Between Internet Radicalization and Violence |date=28 April 2019 |publisher=[[Southern Poverty Law Center]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/262398 |title=Synagogue shooter accused Jews of plotting 'European genocide' |date=29 April 2019 |publisher=[[Arutz Sheva]]}}</ref>

The perpetrator of the [[2019 El Paso shooting]] that killed 23 and injured another 23<ref name="NYT23">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/04/26/business/ap-mass-shooting-texas.html|title=El Paso Shooting Victim Dies Months Later, Death Toll Now 23|work=The New York Times|date=26 April 2020|access-date=26 April 2020}}</ref> had published a manifesto expressing support for the Christchurch shooter and his manifesto, saying the El Paso attack was in response to a "Hispanic invasion of Texas ... defending my country from cultural and ethnic replacement.... the Hispanic community was not my target before I read ''The Great Replacement''."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2019/08/03/el-paso-shooting-suspect-may-have-authored-manifesto-containing-white-nationalist-talking|title=El Paso Shooting Suspect May Have Authored Manifesto Containing White Nationalist Talking Points|date=3 August 2019|access-date=3 August 2019|work=Hatewatch|publisher=[[Southern Poverty Law Center]]|last=Barrouquere|first=Brett}}</ref> Several commentators noted that the manifesto echoed themes in [[Donald Trump]]'s campaign speeches, including repeated claims of a Hispanic invasion along with general extremism and hateful language, whose proponents have been emboldened and mobilized by Trump's rhetoric<ref name="echoed" /><ref>{{cite web|last1=Politi|first1=Daniel|title=El Paso Suspect Reportedly a Trump Supporter Who Wrote Racist, Anti-Immigrant Manifesto|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2019/08/el-paso-suspect-shooter-trump-racist-manifesto.html|website=[[Slate (website)|Slate]]|access-date=4 August 2019|date=3 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Evans|first1=Robert|author-link = Robert Evans (journalist)|title=The El Paso Shooting and the Gamification of Terror|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/americas/2019/08/04/the-el-paso-shooting-and-the-gamification-of-terror/|website=[[Bellingcat]]|access-date=4 August 2019|date=4 August 2019}}</ref> and increasingly frequent talking points in right-wing media outlets.<ref name="common" /> Trump, in turn, called for "strong background checks, perhaps marrying this legislation with desperately needed immigration reform", which some commentators said blamed immigration for the massacre.<ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Neil |first1=Luke |title=Trump just blamed the El Paso shooting victims for their own deaths |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/2019/08/05/trump-just-blamed-el-paso-shooting-victims-their-own-deaths/ |access-date=6 August 2019 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=5 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref>

The suspect in the [[2022 Buffalo shooting]] that killed ten people and injured three others blamed Jews and African-Americans for white genocide in a manifesto, according to law enforcement officials. He had taken inspiration from other far-right mass shooters, whom he regarded as "heroes".<ref name=NYTLive>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/live/2022/05/14/nyregion/buffalo-shooting|title=Live Updates: Gunman Kills 10 at Buffalo Supermarket in Racist Attack|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=14 May 2022|accessdate=14 May 2022}}</ref>

=== Europe ===
[[File:Oslo view of city after July 2011 bombing.jpg|thumb|The 2011 Oslo bombing killed eight people and injured at least 209. A few hours later, the attacker shot and killed 69 others, all but 14 of whom were teenagers.<ref name="Norway">{{cite news|author=Clive Williams|date=26 July 2011|title=Deadly, cruel lesson from Norway|work=The Australian|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/features/deadly-cruel-lesson-from-norway/story-e6frg6z6-1226101590303|url-status=live|access-date=27 July 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726235141/http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/features/deadly-cruel-lesson-from-norway/story-e6frg6z6-1226101590303|archive-date=26 July 2011}}</ref>]]

[[Anders Behring Breivik]], the perpetrator of the [[2011 Norway attacks]], had participated for years in debates on Internet forums and spoken against Islam and immigration.<ref name="Norway" /> He wrote a 1,518-page [[compendium]] including frequent mentions of alleged ongoing genocide against white Europeans.<ref name="PaulJ" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Rayner|first=Gordon|date=24 July 2011|title=Norway killer Anders Behring Breivik called Gordon Brown and Prince Charles 'traitors'|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/norway/8658431/Norway-killer-Anders-Behring-Breivik-called-Gordon-Brown-and-Prince-Charles-traitors.html|url-status=live|access-date=11 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421002604/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/norway/8658431/Norway-killer-Anders-Behring-Breivik-called-Gordon-Brown-and-Prince-Charles-traitors.html|archive-date=21 April 2012}}</ref> Analysts described him as having [[Islamophobic]] views and a hatred of Islam,<ref>{{cite web|author=Sindre Bangstad|title=After Anders Breivik's conviction, Norway must confront Islamophobia|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2012/aug/28/anders-breivik-norway-islamophobia-muslims|access-date=24 July 2016|work=The Guardian|date=28 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=21 August 2011|title=AFP: Norway remembers 77 victims a month after massacre|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5j0D-1Q4Rg2RzAcXi1tCYJgK3PNuw?docId=CNG.d605a2923da5a34248120fc4eb7dc2c7.691|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120107032431/https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5j0D-1Q4Rg2RzAcXi1tCYJgK3PNuw?docId=CNG.d605a2923da5a34248120fc4eb7dc2c7.691|archive-date=7 January 2012|access-date=21 January 2012}}</ref> and as someone who considered himself as a knight dedicated to stemming the tide of Muslim immigration into Europe.<ref>{{cite web|author=Starla Muhammad|date=19 August 2011|title=Tragedy in Norway Borne Out of Seeds of Racism and Intolerance in UK, EU|url=http://newamericamedia.org/2011/08/tragedy-in-norway-borne-out-of-seeds-of-racism-and-intolerance-in-uk-eu.php|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120105004806/http://newamericamedia.org/2011/08/tragedy-in-norway-borne-out-of-seeds-of-racism-and-intolerance-in-uk-eu.php|archive-date=5 January 2012|access-date=21 January 2012|publisher=New America Media}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Godfrey|first=Hannah|date=19 August 2011|title=Utøya island shooting victims return to scene of Breivik's killing spree|work=The Guardian|location=London|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/aug/19/utoya-island-shooting-victims-return}}</ref> The text copies sections of the [[Unabomber manifesto]], without giving credit, while substituting the words "cultural Marxists" for "leftists" and "Muslims" for "black people".<ref>{{cite web|title=Massedrapsmannen kopierte "Unabomberen" ord for ord|date=24 July 2011|url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/norge/1.7725223|access-date=24 July 2011|publisher=Nrk.no}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' described American influences in the writings, noting that the compendium mentions the anti-Islamist American [[Robert Spencer (author)|Robert Spencer]] 64 times and cites Spencer's works at great length.<ref name="scottshane">{{cite news|last=Shane|first=Scott|date=24 July 2011|title=Killings in Norway Spotlight Anti-Muslim Thought in U.S.|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/25/us/25debate.html|access-date=10 April 2017}}</ref> The work of [[Bat Ye'or]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Craig S.|date=20 February 2005|title=Europe's Jews Seek Solace on the Right|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/02/20/weekinreview/20smit.html}}</ref> is cited dozens of times.<ref>{{cite web|last=Archer|first=Toby|date=25 July 2011|title=Breivik's Swamp|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/articles/2011/07/25/breivik_s_swamp?page=0,1|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110910205259/http://www.foreignpolicy.com/articles/2011/07/25/breivik_s_swamp?page=0%2C1|archive-date=10 September 2011|work=[[Foreign Policy (magazine)|Foreign Policy]]}}</ref> It regards [[Islam]] and "[[Cultural Marxism conspiracy theory|cultural Marxism]]" as the enemy and argues for the annihilation of "[[Eurabia]]" and [[multiculturalism]], to preserve a [[Christendom|Christian Europe]].<ref name="Goodman">{{cite news|last1=Mala|first1=Elisa|last2=Goodman|first2=J David|date=22 July 2011|title=At Least 80 Are Dead in Norway Shooting|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/23/world/europe/23oslo.html|url-status=live|access-date=20 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724004316/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/23/world/europe/23oslo.html|archive-date=24 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Beaumont|first=Peter|author-link=Peter Beaumont (journalist)|date=23 July 2011|title=Anders Behring Breivik: profile of a mass murderer|work=The Guardian|location=UK|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/jul/23/anders-behring-breivik-norway-attacks|url-status=live|access-date=25 July 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724221409/http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2011/jul/23/anders-behring-breivik-norway-attacks|archive-date=24 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Saunders|first=Debra J|date=26 July 2011|title=Norwegian Crime and Punishment|newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2011/07/25/ED111KENUV.DTL|quote=the anti-multiculturalism, anti-Muslim and anti-Marxist message of his 1,500-page manifesto}}</ref>

=== New Zealand ===
The perpetrator of the [[Christchurch mosque shootings]] that killed 51 and injured 40 explained in a manifesto that he carried out the attack to fight ongoing "white genocide" by foreign "invaders".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weill|first1=Kelly|last2=Sommer|first2=Will|date=15 March 2019|title=Mosque Attack Video Linked to 'White Genocide' Rant|language=en|agency=The Daily Beast|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/christchurch-shootings-mosque-attack-video-linked-to-white-genocide-rant|access-date=22 March 2019}}</ref> He had forwarded stories about white women's low fertility rates on his social media accounts. Photographs from his initial court appearance showed him making the [[OK gesture#White power symbol|"OK" symbol]] appropriated by white supremacists with his fingers.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Howe|first1=Suzette|last2=Melendez|first2=Pilar|last3=Latza Nadeau|first3=Barbie|date=15 March 2019|title=New Zealand Mosque Shooting Suspect Brenton Tarrant Flashes White Power Sign in Court|language=en|agency=The Daily Beast|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/brenton-tarrant-idd-new-zealand-shooting-suspect|access-date=22 March 2019}}</ref>

== Criticism and resistance ==
White genocide is a myth based on false science, false history, and hatred.<ref name="PerryB" /><ref name="myth" /><ref name="RisingE">{{cite book |last1=Saslow |first1=Eli |url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/557516/rising-out-of-hatred-by-eli-saslow/9780385542869/ |title=Rising out of hatred: the awakening of a former white nationalist |date=September 2018 |publisher=Penguin Random House |isbn=978-0385542876|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106231457/https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/557516/rising-out-of-hatred-by-eli-saslow/9780385542869/ |archive-date=6 November 2018 }}</ref> White people are not dying out, will not die out, and are not facing extermination.<ref name="RisingE" /><ref name="MarcotteA">{{cite news |last1=Marcotte |first1=Amanda |title=Donald Trump's "white genocide" rhetoric: A dangerous escalation of racism |url=https://www.salon.com/2018/08/27/donald-trumps-white-genocide-rhetoric-a-dangerous-escalation-of-racism/ |work=Salon |date=27 August 2018 |language=en}}</ref>{{Better source needed|reason=The current source is insufficiently reliable ([[WP:NOTRS]]).|date=September 2022}}<ref name="DeVegaC" />{{Better source needed|reason=The current source is insufficiently reliable ([[WP:NOTRS]]).|date=September 2022}} White supremacists claim that diversity is equivalent to white genocide.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Diversity = White Genocide {{!}} ADL |url=https://www.adl.org/resources/hate-symbol/diversity-white-genocide |access-date=2022-09-29 |website=www.adl.org |language=en}}</ref> Scholars describe white supremacists as fabricating paranoid claims that their survival as a race is threatened, for example by, "individualism, celibacy, feminism and other forms of sex-role confusion, misplaced environmentalism, and white demonization and guilt," all of which are claimed to promote reproductive failure.<ref name="PannellJ">{{cite journal |last1=Pannell |first1=Justin |last2=Brod |first2=Adam |last3=Horton |first3=Reina Hirose |title=The Conception of Race in White Supremacist Discourse: A Critical Corpus Analysis with Teaching Implications |journal=TESOL Working Paper Series |date=2018 |volume=16 |pages=40–61 |url=https://www.hpu.edu/research-publications/tesol-working-papers/2018/03pannell-brod-horton.pdf}}</ref>

[[File:McVeigh mugshot.jpg|thumb|Timothy McVeigh]]

White genocide conspiracy theory frames evidence of declining birth rates in support of extremist views and calls to violence.<ref name="BetuelE">{{cite web |last1=Betuel |first1=Emma |title=CDC Data on Declining US Fertility Rate Is Being Used by White Nationalists |date=13 January 2019 |url=https://www.inverse.com/article/52409-cdc-fertility-report-race-breakdown-white-nationalism |website=Inverse |language=en}}</ref> White supremacists are successfully constructing false narratives of genocide to incite violence at an increasing rate.<ref name="PerryB">{{cite book |last1=Perry |first1=Barbara |editor1-last=Ferber |editor1-first=Abby L. |title=Home-grown hate: gender and organized racism |date=November 2003 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-203-64405-8 |chapter-url={{Google books|LCI6Y-4BmT0C|page=75|plainurl=yes}} |chapter='White Genocide': White Supremacists and the Politics of Reproduction |pages=75–95 |doi=10.4324/9780203644058 }}</ref> Literature propounding the white genocide conspiracy theory has incited violence; ''[[The Turner Diaries]],'' for instance, is responsible for inciting many violent crimes, including those of [[Timothy McVeigh]].{{r|Darby Telegraph}}<ref name="Berger">{{cite journal |last1=Berger |first1=J.M. |title=The Turner Legacy: The Storied Origins and Enduring Impact of White Nationalism's Deadly Bible |journal=Terrorism and Counter-Terrorism Studies |date=2016 |volume=7 |issue=8 |doi=10.19165/2016.1.11 |doi-access=free }}</ref><ref name="MarcotteA" />{{Better source needed|reason=The current source is insufficiently reliable ([[WP:NOTRS]]).|date=September 2022}}<ref name="bellingcat-evans">{{cite web |last1=Evans |first1=Robert |author-link=Robert Evans (journalist) |date=4 August 2019 |title=The El Paso Shooting and the Gamification of Terror |url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/americas/2019/08/04/the-el-paso-shooting-and-the-gamification-of-terror/ |access-date=24 July 2022 |website=[[Bellingcat]]}}</ref> The US Republican Party as led by Donald Trump has repeatedly and openly courted white supremacists and endorsed the falsehoods they promote, including those of white genocide.<ref name="TaylorK">{{cite journal |last1=Taylor |first1=Keeanga-Yamahtta |title=The White Power Presidency: Race and Class in the Trump Era |journal=New Political Science |date=16 February 2018 |volume=40 |issue=1 |pages=103–112 |doi=10.1080/07393148.2018.1420555 |s2cid=149300385 }}</ref>

In October 2016, [[Sanjiv Bhattacharya]] analyzed the belief in the conspiracy theory amongst the [[alt-right]]. While considering the prospect that non-Hispanic whites will be less than 50% of the US population by 2044; Bhattacharya, a British journalist, pointed out the racist hypocrisy in the statement "Diversity equals white genocide", discussing how the "alt right loves to evoke genocide while harbouring [[Holocaust deniers]]".<ref>{{cite news|title='Call me a racist, but don't say I'm a Buddhist': meet America's alt right |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/oct/09/call-me-a-racist-but-dont-say-im-a-buddhist-meet-the-alt-right |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |author=Bhattacharya, Sanjiv|author-link=Sanjiv Bhattacharya|date=9 October 2016}}</ref>

Around the Christmas period of 2016, [[George Ciccariello-Maher]], an American political scientist, satirically tweeted "All I Want for Christmas is White Genocide". As a result of the ensuing controversy, Ciccariello-Maher resigned from his job as an associate professor of [[politics]] and [[global studies]] at [[Drexel University]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gray |first1=Melissa |title=Drexel professor resigns amid threats over controversial tweets |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2017/12/28/us/drexel-university-professor-resigns/index.html |access-date=9 August 2020 |agency=[[CNN]] |date=29 December 2017}}</ref> Ciccariello-Maher continued to strongly oppose the conspiracy theory, claiming that it was "invented by white supremacists and used to denounce everything from [[inter-racial relationships]] to multicultural policies."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/history-professor-twitter-storm-white-genocide-death-threats-george-ciccariello-maher-a7497301.html |title='All I want for Christmas is white genocide': Professor receives death threats after mocking supremacists |date=27 December 2016 |newspaper=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> He has labelled the concept as a "figment of the racist imagination" and claimed that "it should be mocked."<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://time.com/4618146/drexel-professor-white-genocide-tweet/ |title=A Drexel Professor Tweeted That He Wants 'White Genocide' for Christmas |date=26 December 2016 |magazine=[[TIME]]}}</ref>

[[Derek Black]], an American former white supremacist and godson of [[David Duke]], after initially supporting and helping to popularize the concept,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/the-white-flight-of-derek-black/2016/10/15/ed5f906a-8f3b-11e6-a6a3-d50061aa9fae_story.html |title=The white flight of Derek Black |date=15 October 2016 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref><ref name="NEA">{{cite news|title=How Higher Education Helped Derek Black Renounce White Supremacy |url=http://neatoday.org/2018/09/19/how-higher-education-helped-derek-black-renounce-white-supremacy/ |publisher=[[NEA Today]] |date=19 September 2018}}</ref> has renounced and opposed the white genocide conspiracy theory.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/arts/books/2018/09/18/derek-blackwas-scion-racism-renounced-rising-hatred-tells-story |title=Derek Black was the scion of racism — then renounced it; 'Rising Out of Hatred' tells his story |date=17 September 2018 |newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |access-date=21 September 2018 |archive-date=20 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190820081235/https://www.dallasnews.com/arts/books/2018/09/18/derek-blackwas-scion-racism-renounced-rising-hatred-tells-story |url-status=dead }}</ref> Black has claimed that the concept was about pushing [[white nationalists]] into a false and overt [[paranoia]] about [[demographics of the United States]].<ref name="MarcotteA" />{{Better source needed|reason=The current source is insufficiently reliable ([[WP:NOTRS]]).|date=September 2022}} [[Eli Saslow]], an American journalist who worked with Black on his 2018 book ''Rising out of Hatred'', has spoken against the conspiracy theory, labelling it as a "really effective" form of propaganda or indoctrination. He stated that "unfortunately, in part because it's built upon a very real and dark truth in [[American history]]—which is that [[white supremacy]] has always been a big part of what this country is—white nationalists were able to start capitalizing on that."<ref>{{cite news|title=The White Nationalist Heir Who Rejected His Dad's Vile Bigotry |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/yw4dkb/the-white-nationalist-heir-who-rejected-his-dads-vile-bigotry |publisher=[[Vice Media]] |date=18 September 2018}}</ref> Saslow has claimed the conspiracy theory is a way to "sanitize" [[white America]]'s history of racism and violence, by focusing on the "ways that white people are under attack in this country," including "white genocide" and "[[Executive Order 13767|building a wall]]".<ref name="NEA" />

In January 2019, Democratic [[Philadelphia City Council]] member [[Kenyatta Johnson]] labelled the [[Ku Klux Klan]]'s distribution of "white genocide" promotional material in black neighborhoods of Philadelphia as an "upsetting and disgusting" act.<ref name="KKK material" /> In June 2019, Canadian author [[Naomi Klein]] addressed the narrative of "white genocide", criticizing the concept as an attack on women's reproductive freedom, in that it wished to deny [[abortion rights]] to white women having white children, while seeking to suppress non-white immigrant birthrates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2019/06/02/news/naomi_klein_dig_festival_2019-227798940/|title=Naomi Klein: "Economia e ambiente, serve un'unica rivoluzione globale" |language=it|trans-title=Naomi Klein: "Economy and environment, we need a single global revolution"|publisher=[[la Repubblica]]|date=2 June 2019}}</ref> The following month, critical theorist [[Bernard Harcourt]] detailed how the American [[New Right#United States|New Right]] was seeking to orient its political message around the fear of a white genocide occurring. He proposed that "neo-fascist, white supremacist, revolutionary language" was becoming mainstream and was in effect "starting to change the way people are willing to express themselves", including President Trump.<ref>{{cite news|title=Trump the storyteller: His gift for narrative is why he may win again |url=https://www.salon.com/2019/07/13/trump-the-storyteller-his-gift-for-narrative-is-why-he-may-win-again/ |work=[[Salon (magazine)|Salon]]|date=13 July 2019}}</ref>{{Better source needed|reason=The current source is insufficiently reliable ([[WP:NOTRS]]).|date=September 2022}}

In March 2019, journalist [[Adam Serwer]] suggested that the conspiracy theory did not sincerely refer to "mass murder, ethnic cleansing, or even violence," but rather to a perceived "loss of political and [[cultural hegemony]] in countries that white supremacists think should belong to white people by law." Serwer proposed that the conspiracy was "a kind of projection, a paranoia that the past genocide, colonialism, and [[ethnic cleansing]] forced on the West's former subjects will be visited upon it."<ref name="Serwer1">{{cite news|title=Nazis Have Always Been Trolls |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/03/mosque-shooter-troll-like-original-nazis/585415/ |work=[[The Atlantic]] |author=Serwer, Adam|author-link=Adam Serwer|date=21 March 2016}}</ref><ref name="Serwer2">{{cite news |title=Harvard fellow examines rise — and roots — of white supremacy |url=https://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2019/03/harvard-fellow-examines-rise-and-roots-of-white-supremacy/ |access-date=27 August 2019 |work=Harvard Gazette |date=18 March 2019}}</ref> The same month, [[Farhad Manjoo]] detailed how "white-extinction theory" was nonsense. Proposing that the "white genocide" label had "failed to take off", proving ineffective for conspiracy theorists attempting to push the narrative. Manjoo, an American journalist, suggested that the "[[Great Replacement]]" (which the Christchurch mosque shooter used for a manifesto title) was a softer reinvention, being to the white genocide conspiracy theory what the term [[Identitarian]] is to "white supremacist".<ref>{{cite news|title=The White-Extinction Conspiracy Theory Is Bonkers |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/20/opinion/new-zealand-great-replacement.html |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |author=Manjoo, Farhad |author-link=Farhad Manjoo|date=20 March 2019}}</ref>

[[File:Thilo Sarrazin030709.jpg|thumb|Thilo Sarrazin in 2009]]

In April 2019, British academic [[Elif Shafak]] detailed how [[Renaud Camus]]' theory of the [[Great Replacement]] has created an ideological worldview for the far-right to amplify into a "white genocide" narrative in the West. Shafak argues that the conspiracy theory is also embedded in the works of [[Thilo Sarrazin]], such as ''[[Germany Abolishes Itself]]'' and 2018's ''[[Hostile Takeover: How Islam Impedes Progress and Threatens Society|Hostile Takeover]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=To understand the far right, look to their bookshelves   |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/apr/01/far-right-bookshelves-jordan-peterson-thilo-sarrazin |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |author=Shafak, Elif|author-link=Elif Shafak|date=1 April 2019}}</ref> Later that month, [[Jonathan Freedland]] and [[Mehdi Hasan]] released a joint analysis of far-right extremism and the ideology behind "white genocide". Discussing Pittsburgh synagogue shooter, [[Robert Gregory Bowers]], and his rhetoric, Freeland and Hasan, both political journalists, labelled the conspiracy theory as racist and unhinged and argued that it had both the Muslim and Jewish "communities in its murderous sights". They concluded that both groups should "stand and fight it together".<ref>{{cite news|title=Muslims and Jews face a common threat from white supremacists. We must fight it together  |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/apr/03/muslims-jews-white-supremacists |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |author1=Freedlan, Jonathan|author-link1=Jonathan Freedland|author2=Hasan, Mehdi|author-link2=Mehdi Hasan|date=3 April 2019}}</ref>

In May 2019, political commentator [[Nick Cohen]] analyzed how "white genocide" narratives created anti-immigrant and societal sexual tension. He argued that the conspiracy theory was an effective form of racism and propaganda, which had penetrated [[Viktor Orbán]]'s Hungarian government, but revealed a far-right paranoia that European men were not [[virile]] enough.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/may/18/when-the-far-right-crack-rape-jokes-part-of-a-systemic-bid-to-demean|title=When the far right crack rape jokes, it's part of a systemic bid to demean |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|author=Cohen, Nick|author-link=Nick Cohen|date=18 May 2019}}</ref> In June 2019, professor of economics [[Jonathan Portes]], while describing the concept as a "lunatic" conspiracy theory, detailed how more respectable versions of "white genocide" were being promoted by academic and media figures, and therefore pushing the idea further into mainstream discourse.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/jun/30/tragedy-is-inevitable-if-we-fear-migration-rather-than-celebrate-its-benefits|title=Tragedy is inevitable if we fear migration rather than celebrate its benefits |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|author=Portes, Jonathan|author-link=Jonathan Portes|date=30 June 2019}}</ref>

